{{Orphan|date=November 2016}}
'''Dyke Action Machine!''' or '''DAM!''' is a [[public art]] and [[Activism|activist]] duo made up of [[designer]] [[Carrie Moyer]] and [[photographer]] Sue Schaffner. DAM! gained notoriety in the 1990s for using commercial photography styling with lesbian imagery in public art.
== History == Sue Schaffner and Carrie Moyer formed Dyke Action Machine! (DAM!) in 1991 in [[New York City]]. The duo created [[Radical feminism|radical feminist]] [[public art]], putting images of lesbians into commercialized styles and settings.<ref name=":0" /> Together with groups like [[Guerrilla Girls|Guerilla Girls]] and Toxic Titties, DAM! resisted [[sexism]] and [[consumerism]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Raizada|first=Kristen|date=2007-01-01|title=An Interview with the Guerrilla Girls, Dyke Action Machine (DAM!), and the Toxic Titties|jstor=4317230|journal=NWSA Journal|volume=19|issue=1|pages=39–58}}</ref> DAM! specifically targeted [[lesbophobia]], the marginalization of lesbians not only in favor of heterosexuality but also within LGBT circles, where Schaffner and Moyer saw the male homosexual as privileged.<ref name=":2" /> DAM! has been described as intentionally pluralistic, embracing many identities and issues.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nguyen|first=Tram|date=2013|title=From SlutWalks to SuicideGirls: Feminist Resistance in the Third Wave and Postfeminist Era|jstor=23611512|journal=Women's Studies Quarterly|volume=41|issue=3/4|pages=157–172}}</ref>
With Schaffner's experience as a commercial photographer and Moyer's work as a designer and painter, the duo captured and created images reminiscent of commercial advertising but delivered messages that raised the profile of lesbians. This material was then placed where ads were typically seen, such as [[bus stop]]s, [[telephone booth]]s, and construction site barricades.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sNCJAwAAQBAJ|title=The Queer Encyclopedia of the Visual Arts|last=Summers|first=Claude J.|date=2004|publisher=Cleis Press|isbn=9781573441919|pages=256|language=en}}</ref> DAM!'s method of presenting lesbian activist art in typically commercial landscapes creates an effect described by some as "slick subvertising"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bitchmedia.org/issue/10|title=Profile: Dyke Action Machine—Slick subvertising on the streets of New York City|last=Jervis|first=Lisa|year=1999|website=Bitch Magazine Volume 10|access-date=2016-06-30}}</ref> and "agit-prop".<ref>Blake, Nayland and Lawrence Rinder. "[http://archive.bampfa.berkeley.edu/exhibition/InaDifferentLight/An_Introduction_to_In_a_Different_Light_by_Lawrence_Rinder.pdf In a Different Light]." Exhibition Catalog. University of California, Berkeley Art Museum. January 11 – April 19, 1995.</ref> Schaffner and Moyer remained anonymous for eight years, signing their work only with Dyke Action Machine!.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kbmPBQAAQBAJ|title=Politisierung der Kunst: Avantgarde und US-Kunstwelt|last=Hieber|first=Lutz|date=2014-11-20|publisher=Springer-Verlag|isbn=9783658020156|language=de}}</ref> Among their influences for their work were [[Gran Fury]], [[Barbara Kruger]], and Fran Winant.<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rando|first=Flavia|date=1996-01-01|title=Reflections on a Name: We're Here: Gay and Lesbian Presence in Art and Art History|jstor=777647|journal=Art Journal|volume=55|issue=4|pages=8–10|doi=10.2307/777647}}</ref> The duo is mainly active in the New York City area, although their work has been shown internationally and they make some available to be downloaded and distributed by anyone.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thescavenger.net/arts/performance/411-agitprop-artist-carrie-moyer-71356.html|title=Agitprop artist: Carrie Moyer|last=Fox|first=Katrina|date=2010-08-14|website=The Scavenger|access-date=2016-07-04}}</ref>
The work of Dyke Action Machine! is held at the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQpraD6b0XoC|title=Mixing Messages|last=Lupton|first=Ellen|last2=Museum|first2=Cooper-Hewitt|date=1996-09-01|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|isbn=9781568980997|language=en}}</ref> It has been included in anthologies and encyclopedias of queer and lesbian art, where their work has been discussed alongside LGBT artist activists Chloe Atkins, Kay Shumack, Marion Moore, Jill Posener, the Australian Word of Mouth Collective.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2NQAAAAMAAJ|title=Lesbian Art in America: A Contemporary History|last=Hammond|first=Harmony|date=2000|publisher=Random House Incorporated|isbn=9780847822485|language=en}}</ref> In 2000, Schaffner and Moyer won a Creative Capital award for visual arts to create ''Gynadome: A Separate Paradise''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://creative-capital.org/projects/printable/264|title=Project – Gynadome: A Separate Paradise|website=Creative Capital – Investing in Artists who Shape the Future|access-date=2016-06-30}}</ref>
== Exhibitions == * 1999: ''Gender Trouble (Unbehagen der Geschlechter)'' Neuer Aachener Kunstverein, [[Aachen]], Germany<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.neueraachenerkunstverein.de/content/1999/ausstellungen/unbehagen/|title=Unbehagen|last=Neuer Aachener Kunstverein|first=|website=www.neueraachenerkunstverein.de|access-date=2016-06-30}}</ref> * 2001–2: ''Straight to Hell: 10 Years of Dyke Action Machine!'' [[Yerba Buena Center for the Arts]], [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], California; Diverseworks, [[Houston]], Texas<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/straight-to-hell-10-years-of-dyke-action-machine-may-4-july-14-2002/oclc/50209391&referer=brief_results|title=Straight to hell: 10 years of Dyke Action Machine! : May 4 – July 14, 2002.|last=Dyke Action Machine|last2=Moyer|first2=Carrie|last3=Schaffner|first3=Sue|last4=Atkins|first4=Robert|last5=Center for the Arts at Yerba Buena Gardens|date=2002-01-01|isbn=0971971102|language=English}}</ref> * 2008: ''Break the rules!'' Mannheimer Kunstverein, [[Mannheim]], Germany<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/break-the-rules-sammlungen-hiebertheising-61-322008-mannheimer-kunstverein/oclc/298777058|title=Break the rules!: Sammlungen Hieber/Theising, 6.1.-3.2.2008, Mannheimer Kunstverein|date=2008-01-01|publisher=Mannheimer Kunstverein|location=Mannheim|language=German}}</ref>
