{{Infobox book | name = Miscellaneous Babylonian Inscriptions | title_orig = | translator = | image = Semitic Babylonian contract-tablet.jpg | caption = Semitic Babylonian contract-tablet inscribed in the reign of Hammurabi | author = [[George Aaron Barton]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Language]], [[Sumerology]], [[Cuneiform studies]], [[Translation]] | genre = | publisher = [[Yale University Press]], [[Oxford University Press]] | pub_date = August 1918 | media_type = print ([[hardback]]) | pages = 177pp (first edition) | isbn = 978-1-148-59897-0 | dewey= 492/.1 | congress= PJ3711 .Y34 1983 | oclc= 2539495 }} [[File:Hymn Iddin-Dagan Louvre AO8864.jpg|thumb|Sumerian Cuneiform Cylinder similar to the "Barton Cylinder"]] '''''Miscellaneous Babylonian Inscriptions''''' is a [[1918 in literature|1918]], [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] [[linguistics]] and [[mythology]] book written by [[George Aaron Barton]].<ref name="Barton1918">{{cite book|author=George Aaron Barton|title=Miscellaneous Babylonian Inscriptions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nn5hAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=23 May 2011|year=1918|publisher=Yale University Press}}</ref>
It was first published by [[Yale University Press]] in the United States and deals with commentary and translations of twelve [[cuneiform]], Sumerian [[myth]]s and texts discovered by the [[University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]] excavations at the [[temple]] [[library]] at [[Nippur]].<ref name="Meade1974">{{cite book|author=C. Wade Meade|title=Road to Babylon: Development of U.S. Assyriology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iuAUAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA87|accessdate=5 June 2011|year=1974|publisher=Brill Archive|isbn=978-90-04-03858-5|pages=87–}}</ref> Many of the texts are extremely archaic, especially the [[Barton Cylinder]], which [[Samuel Noah Kramer]] suggested may date as early as 2500 BC.<ref name="Kramer1961">{{cite book|author=Samuel Noah Kramer|title=Sumerian Mythology: a study of spiritual and literary achievement in the third millennium B.C.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t16tDOHZLLEC&pg=PA148|accessdate=5 June 2011|year=1961|publisher=Forgotten Books|isbn=978-1-60506-049-1|pages=28 & 148}}</ref> A more modern dating by [[Joan Goodnick Westenholz]] has suggested the cylinder dates to around 2400 BC.<ref name="BorrásBarcelona2000">{{cite book|author1=Miguel Ángel Borrás|author2=Centre de Cultura Contemporània de Barcelona|title=La fundación de la ciudad: mitos y ritos en el mundo antiguo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3yPVFGPr0aoC&pg=PA46|accessdate=5 June 2011|year=2000|publisher=Edicions UPC|isbn=978-84-8301-387-8|pages=46–}}</ref>
