{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}} {{Infobox NRHP | name = Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute | nrhp_type = | image = Munson-Williams-Proctor Institute.jpg | caption = Munson-Williams-Proctor Institute Museum of Art Building | location= 310 Genesee St., [[Utica, New York]] | coordinates = {{coord|43|5|49|N|75|14|29|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = New York#USA | built = 1960 | architect = Johnson, Philip | architecture = International-style | added = September 9, 2010 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 10000727<ref name="nps">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/listings/20100917.htm|title=National Register of Historic Places Listings|date=2010-09-17|work=WEEKLY LIST OF ACTIONS TAKEN ON PROPERTIES: 9/07/10 THROUGH 9/10/10|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref> }} The '''Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute''' (MWPAI) is a regional fine [[Arts centre|arts center]] founded in 1919 and located in [[Utica, New York]]. The institute has three program divisions: *Museum of art *Performing arts *School of art
==Museum of art== The museum of art has a substantial permanent collection of internationally recognized works. They are exhibited in the Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute Museum of Art Building. It is an [[International style (architecture)|International-style]] building designed by [[architect]] [[Philip Johnson]] and completed in 1960. A model of the building was exhibited in the United States Pavilion at the [[Expo 58|Brussels' World's Fair of 1958]]. It is a 60,000 sqft<ref>Asad Syrkett, http://www.architecturalrecord.com/articles/5335-a-golden-anniversary-for-a-philip-johnson-museum</ref> square and supported by eight external ferro-concrete piers, or two on each side. The exterior structural members are clad in [[bronze]] and "black" Canadian [[granite]]. The windowless cube is set above windowed office areas recessed in a dry moat, giving a "floating" effect. The interior features a two-story central courtyard, illuminated by a skylight, known as the Edward Wales Root Sculpture Court. It also holds an [[auditorium]] seating 271.<ref name="NysNrhpNom">{{cite web | url = https://cris.parks.ny.gov/ | title = Cultural Resource Information System (CRIS)| publisher = [[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]| format = Searchable database| accessdate = 2016-08-01}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web | url = https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=26073&q=false | title = National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Munson-Williams-Proctor Arts Institute | accessdate = 2016-08-01 | author = Rand Carter and Travis Bowman| format = PDF| date=December 2009}} and [https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=25868&q=false ''Accompanying five photographs'']</ref> It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2010.<ref name="nps"/>
Next-door is a [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]]-[[Victorian era|era]] [[Italianate]] mansion called ''[[Fountain Elms]]'', listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1972.<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> It houses the MWPAI [[decorative arts]] collection. It is connected to the Museum of Art building by an education wing built in 1995.
The museum has an extensive collection of European and American art. A highlight of the permanent collection is the first of the two original sets of [[Thomas Cole]]'s famous series of paintings titled ''[[The Voyage of Life]]'': The second set is at the [[National Gallery]] [[Washington, DC.]]
==PrattMWP== The institute also has a program called ''Pratt at Munson-Williams-Proctor'' (MWP) which allows students to study for two years in [[Utica, New York]], called a "Foundations Program", before completing their [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree at [[Pratt Institute]]'s main campus in [[Brooklyn, New York]]. PrattMWP is accredited by the [[National Association of Schools of Art and Design]], [[Middle States Association]], and [[New York State Education Department]].
